english:
  title: On the Similarities and Differences Between Confucianism and Buddhism
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The ancient scholars said, "The ways of Confucianism and Buddhism resemble each other phrase by phrase, yet differ deed by deed." Let me now expand upon this observation.

    Both we and they speak of emptiness—yet our emptiness contains being, while theirs empties into nothingness. Both speak of stillness—yet our stillness resonates with response, while theirs stills into extinction. We speak of knowing and acting; they speak of awakening and cultivation. Our knowing grasps that the principles of all things are complete within my heart. Their awakening realizes that the heart is originally empty, devoid of all things. Our acting follows the principles of things without deviation. Their cultivation severs attachment to things so that they become no burden to the mind.

    We say: "The heart encompasses all principles." They say: "The heart generates all dharmas." What we mean by encompassing all principles is that these principles originally exist within the heart. In stillness, the very substance of these principles is complete; in movement, their function manifests. Thus we say: "Still yet moving, unmoving yet responsive—this is the reason of all things." What they mean by generating dharmas is that these dharmas originally do not exist within the heart, but arise only when encountering external conditions. In stillness, the heart has nowhere to abide; in movement, dharmas arise according to circumstances encountered. Thus they say: "Responding without abiding, the mind is generated" and "When mind arises, all dharmas arise; when mind ceases, all dharmas cease." We regard principle as inherent; they regard dharmas as dependent on conditions. How strange that the words sound the same yet the deeds are so different!

    We say: "We respond to the ten thousand transformations." They say: "We follow all things as they are." The words seem alike, yet the meaning differs greatly. By responding to the ten thousand transformations, we mean that when things approach from without, this heart responds to each according to its proper nature, governing them so that nothing deviates from what is fitting. If there is a son, we cause him to be filial and not a thief. If there is a minister, we make him loyal and not a traitor. Among animals, we make the ox till without goring, the horse carry without biting, the tiger and wolf remain caged so they do not bite people. We regulate each according to its inherent principle.

    But the Buddhist notion of following all things means: let the son be filial or thief as he will; let the minister be loyal or rebel as he will; let the ox till or gore, the horse carry or bite—all happens of itself. I place no hand in the matter. Such is the Buddhist way. They boast of using things without being used by things, yet if given a single coin, they cannot even manage it. Is this not contradictory?

    Then what becomes of Heaven's intent in creating humans as the most spiritual of beings and entrusting them with the duty of nurturing and assisting all things? Though their doctrines twist back and forth with many threads, the essential point is this: we see that heart and principle are one; they see them as two. They see the heart as empty and devoid of principle; we see the heart as empty yet complete with all things. Thus we say: Confucianism is unity; Buddhism is duality. We are continuous; they are fragmented. Yet the heart is one—how can there be real difference between them? It is merely that people perceive rightly or wrongly.

    They ask: "Among the four elements of this body, who is master? Among the six senses and their objects, what is real? In utter darkness opening our eyes, we hear sound all day yet see no form." This is their experiential understanding of the heart. They say: "Speak of existence and where is its trace? Speak of emptiness and what remains? Only in responsive encounter do we truly perceive the root." This is our Confucian experiential understanding of the heart. But tell me: does the heart of the Way have only sound and no form? Or is there a principle residing in the heart as the root of our responses?

    Let students investigate this in their daily conduct, observing where this heart manifests. Through such inquiry, they will naturally discern what is similar and different, what is correct and mistaken between their way and ours. Let me elaborate using the teaching of Master Zhu:

    Though the heart is master of this single body, its vacuous luminosity suffices to oversee all principles under Heaven. Though principle is scattered throughout all things, its subtle function never transcends the single heart of humans. We need not speak of what is internal or external, refined or coarse. Yet should one fail to recognize this heart's spiritual nature and preserve it, darkness and confusion arise, and one cannot fathom the subtlety of all principles. Should one fail to recognize and investigate the subtlety of all principles, narrowness and rigidity result, and one cannot fulfill the heart's completeness. Thus the relationship between principle and its investigation is necessarily interdependent.

    Therefore the sages established teaching to help people silently recognize this heart's spiritual nature and preserve it in dignified, reverent, unified stillness—making this the foundation for investigating principle. They taught people to recognize that principles subtle and manifold exist, and to investigate them through studying, questioning, thinking, and discerning—thus perfecting the work of fulfilling the heart. The large and small mutually contain each other; the moving and still mutually nurture each other. From the beginning there is no discrimination between internal and external, refined and coarse. When genuine effort accumulates over time, sudden illumination arrives, and through it one knows that all is unified and seamless, beyond all such distinctions.

    Yet some dismiss this as shallow and fragmented, preferring instead to hide form and shadow, constructing some exotic doctrine of obscurity and confusion, bewildering and impassable—forcing students to place their hearts outside written words and language, claiming: "The Way must be thus to be obtained." This represents the worst distortion of recent Buddhist learning, using these perversions to corrupt the true practice of our ancestors—illuminating virtue and renewing the people. How grave is this error! Master Zhu's words, thoroughly reasoned and clearly expressed, reward the deep attention of students who will naturally come to understand them.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The "four elements" (四大) refer to the Buddhist concept of the material world composed of earth, water, fire, and wind—the fundamental components of physical existence.
  - key: ''
    value: The "six senses" (六根) and "their objects" (六塵) are Buddhist terminology for the six cognitive faculties and their corresponding objects of perception.
  - key: ''
    value: Jeong Do-jeon lived during the early Joseon period and was a key advisor to its founder; this text represents official Confucian orthodoxy rejecting Buddhist metaphysics in favor of Neo-Confucian philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: The quotation "Responding without abiding, the mind is generated" references the Diamond Sutra, a foundational Buddhist text that Jeong Do-jeon reinterprets through a Confucian lens.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Zhu refers to Zhu Xi (朱子), the great Neo-Confucian philosopher whose synthesis of Confucian thought profoundly influenced Korean and Japanese intellectual traditions.
